Experiment Title

Controlling the Built-in LED of Arduino MKR WiFi 1010 Using the Blynk App Slider

1. Components Used
1. Arduino MKR WiFi 1010

The Arduino MKR WiFi 1010 is a microcontroller board with built-in
Wi-Fi connectivity. It allows the board to connect to wireless networks and communicate with
cloud platforms such as Blynk.

In this experiment, it receives commands from the Blynk application and controls
the brightness of the built-in LED.

2. Built-in LED

The built-in LED is an LED already integrated on the MKR WiFi 1010 board.
It is used as an output device to visually indicate the changes in brightness
according to the slider value sent from the Blynk app.

3. Blynk IoT Application

Blynk is a cloud-based IoT platform that enables users to remotely monitor and
control devices through a smartphone application. In this project, a slider widget
in the Blynk app sends values to the MKR WiFi 1010 over the internet.

4. Wi-Fi Network

A Wi-Fi connection is required for communication between the MKR WiFi 1010
and the Blynk cloud server. The board connects to the network using the SSID and
password provided in the code.

5. WiFiNINA Library

The WiFiNINA library allows the MKR WiFi 1010 to connect to Wi-Fi networks and
manage wireless communication.

6. BlynkSimpleWiFiNINA Library

This library integrates the MKR WiFi 1010 with the Blynk platform.
It handles communication between the microcontroller and the Blynk cloud server.

7. Slider Widget (Virtual Pin V0)

The slider widget in the Blynk application is linked to Virtual Pin V0.
 It sends a numerical value (0–255) to the microcontroller, which is then used
 to adjust the LED brightness.

2. What the Experiment Did

The experiment demonstrated remote control of the built-in LED on an Arduino
MKR WiFi 1010 using the Blynk IoT platform.

The MKR WiFi 1010 first connected to a Wi-Fi network and then established
communication with the Blynk cloud using an authentication token. A slider widget
on the Blynk mobile application was configured on Virtual Pin V0. Whenever the slider position changed, the Blynk app sent a value to the microcontroller.

The function BLYNK_WRITE(V0) received the slider value and converted it into an
integer. The analogWrite() function then used this value to control the brightness
 of the LED through Pulse Width Modulation (PWM). A lower value resulted in a
 dimmer LED, while a higher value increased the brightness.
The current value was also displayed on the Serial Monitor for monitoring purposes.

3. Importance of the Experiment

This experiment is important because it introduces the fundamental concepts of
the Internet of Things (IoT), where physical devices can be controlled remotely
through the internet.

Key learning outcomes include:

Understanding how a microcontroller connects to a Wi-Fi network.

Learning how cloud platforms such as Blynk enable remote device control.

Using virtual pins to exchange data between a mobile application and a
microcontroller.

Implementing PWM control to vary LED brightness.

Gaining practical experience in IoT application development.

The concepts demonstrated in this experiment can be extended to control other
 devices such as smart lights, fans, motors, sensors, and home automation systems.

4. Conclusion

The experiment successfully demonstrated the remote control of the built-in LED
on the Arduino MKR WiFi 1010 using the Blynk mobile application.
By moving a slider widget in the app, different brightness levels were sent through
the Blynk cloud and applied to the LED using PWM. The project provided hands-on
experience with Wi-Fi communication, cloud connectivity, and IoT-based device
control. Overall, the experiment highlighted how IoT technologies can be used to
 monitor and control electronic devices conveniently from anywhere with an internet
  connection.